# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lmdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write finds its main use in operating systems, sharing the physical memory of computers running multiple processes, in the implementation of the fork() system call.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Typically, the new process does not modify any memory and immediately executes a new process, replacing the address space entirely.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] It would waste processor time and memory to copy all of the old process's memory during the fork only to immediately discard the copy.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write can be implemented efficiently using the page table by marking certain pages of memory as read-only and keeping a count of the number of references to the page.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] When data is written to these pages, the operating-system kernel intercepts the write attempt and allocates a new physical page, initialized with the copy-on-write data, although the allocation can be skipped if there is only one reference.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] The kernel then updates the page table with the new (writable) page, decrements the number of references, and performs the write.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] The new allocation ensures that a change in the memory of one process is not visible in another's.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] The copy-on-write technique can be extended to support efficient memory allocation by keeping one page of physical memory filled with zeros.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] When the memory is allocated, all the pages returned refer to the page of zeros and are all marked copy-on-write.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] This way, physical memory is not allocated for the process until data is written, allowing processes to reserve more virtual memory than physical memory and use memory sparsely, at the risk of running out of virtual address space.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] The combined algorithm is similar to demand paging.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write pages are also used in the Linux kernel's same-page merging feature.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] COW is also used in library, application, and system code.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In the PHP programming language, all types except references are implemented as copy-on-write.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] For example, strings and arrays are passed by reference, but when modified, they are duplicated if they have non-zero reference counts.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] This allows them to act as value types without the performance problems of copying on assignment or making them immutable.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In the Qt framework, many types are copy-on-write ("implicitly shared" in Qt's terms).
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Qt uses atomic compare-and-swap operations to increment or decrement the internal reference counter.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Since the copies are cheap, Qt types can often be safely used by multiple threads without the need of locking mechanisms such as mutexes.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] The benefits of COW are thus valid in both single- and multithreaded systems.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In Docker, a set of software for implementing operating-system level virtualization, docker images are built in a layered format, with lower layers being read-only and the upper layer available for editing.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Creating a new image which shares the same base layers as another image does not copy the layers, but instead follows COW principles and allows the two images to share layers until one is edited.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] COW is used as the underlying mechanism in file systems like ZFS, Btrfs, ReFS, and Bcachefs, as well as in logical volume management and database servers such as Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In traditional file systems, modifying a file overwrites the original data blocks in place.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In a copy-on-write (COW) file system, the original blocks remain unchanged.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] When part of a file is modified, only the affected blocks are written to new locations, and metadata is updated to point to them, preserving the original version until it’s no longer needed.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] This approach enables features like snapshots, which capture the state of a file at a specific time without consuming much additional space.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Snapshots typically store only the modified data and are kept close to the original.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] However, they are considered a weak form of incremental backup and cannot replace a full backup.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] In order to create and start new containers quickly, container engines doing OS-level virtualization often perform copy-on-write in storage, either block-level copy-on-write (as described above) or file-level copy-on-write.
[src:lmdb/copy-on-write] Some but not all filesystems support file-level copy-on-write as part of union mounting, including OverlayFS, aufs, GlusterFS, and UnionFS.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:lmdb/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB may also be used concurrently in a multi-threaded or multi-processing environment, with read performance scaling linearly by design.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB databases may have only one writer at a time, however unlike many similar key-value databases, write transactions do *not* block readers, nor do readers block writers.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB is also unusual in that multiple applications on the same system may simultaneously open and use the same LMDB store, as a means to scale up performance.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Also, LMDB does not require a transaction log (thereby increasing write performance by not needing to write data twice) because it maintains data integrity inherently by design.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB's design was first discussed in a 2009 post to the OpenLDAP developer mailing list, in the context of exploring solutions to the cache management difficulty caused by the project's dependence on Berkeley DB.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] A specific goal was to replace the multiple layers of configuration and caching inherent to Berkeley DB's design with a single, automatically managed cache under the control of the host operating system.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Development subsequently began, initially as a fork of a similar implementation from the OpenBSD ldapd project.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The first publicly available version appeared in the OpenLDAP source repository in June 2011.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The project was known as MDB until November 2012, after which it was renamed in order to avoid conflicts with existing software.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Internally LMDB uses B+ tree data structures.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The efficiency of its design and small footprint had the unintended side-effect of providing good write performance as well.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB has an API similar to Berkeley DB and dbm.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB treats the computer's memory as a single address space, shared across multiple processes or threads using shared memory with copy-on-write semantics (known historically as a single-level store).
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Most former modern computing architectures had a 32-bit memory address space, imposing a hard limit of 4 GB on the size of any database that directly mapped into a single-level store.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] However, today's 64-bit processors now mostly implement 48-bit address spaces, giving access to 47-bit addresses or 128 TB of database size, making databases using shared memory useful once again in real-world applications.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The file format of LMDB is, unlike that of Berkeley DB, architecture-dependent.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] This means that a conversion must be done before moving a database from a 32-bit machine to a 64-bit machine, or between computers of differing endianness.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB employs multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) and allows multiple threads within multiple processes to coordinate simultaneous access to a database.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] While write transactions are globally serialized via a mutex, read-only transactions operate in parallel, including in the presence of a write transaction.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] They are entirely wait free except for the first read-only transaction on a thread.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Each thread reading from a database gains ownership of an element in a shared memory array, which it may update to indicate when it is within a transaction.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Writers scan the array to determine the oldest database version the transaction must preserve without requiring direct synchronization with active readers.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] In 2011, Google published software that allowed users to generate micro-benchmarks comparing LevelDB's performance to SQLite and Kyoto Cabinet in different scenarios.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] In 2012, Symas added support for LMDB and Berkeley DB and made the updated benchmarking software publicly available.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The resulting benchmarks showed that LMDB outperformed all other databases in read and batch write operations.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] SQLite with LMDB excelled in write operations, and particularly so on synchronous/transactional writes.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The benchmarks showed the underlying filesystem as having a big influence on performance.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] JFS with an external journal performs well, especially compared to other modern systems like Btrfs and ZFS.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Zimbra has tested back-mdb vs back-hdb performance in OpenLDAP, with LMDB clearly outperforming the BDB based back-hdb.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Many other OpenLDAP users have observed similar benefits.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Since the initial benchmarking work done in 2012, multiple follow-on tests have been conducted with additional database engines for both in-memory and on-disk workloads characterizing the performance across multiple CPUs and record sizes.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] These tests show that LMDB performance is unmatched on all in-memory workloads and excels in all disk-bound read workloads and disk-bound write workloads using large record sizes.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The benchmark driver code was subsequently published on GitHub and further expanded in database coverage.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB was designed to resist data loss in the face of system and application crashes.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Its copy-on-write approach never overwrites currently-in-use data.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Avoiding overwrites means the structure on disk/storage is always valid, so application or system crashes can never leave the database in a corrupted state.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] In its default mode, at worst, a crash can lose data from the last not-yet-committed write transaction.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Even with all asynchronous modes enabled, it is only an OS catastrophic failure or hardware power-loss event rather than merely an application crash that could potentially result in any data corruption.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Two academic papers from the USENIX OSDI Symposium covered failure modes of DB engines (including LMDB) under a sudden power loss or system crash.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The paper from Pillai et al., did not find any failure in LMDB that would occur in the real-world file systems considered; the single failure identified by the study in LMDB only relates to hypothetical file systems.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The Mai Zheng et al. paper claims to point out failures in LMDB, but the conclusion depends on whether fsync or fdatasync is utilised.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The selection of fsync over fdatasync is a compile-time switch that is not the default behavior in current Linux builds of LMDB but is the default on macOS, *BSD, Android, and Windows.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Default Linux builds of LMDB are, therefore, the only ones vulnerable to the problem discovered by the zhengmai researchers however, LMDB may simply be rebuilt by Linux users to utilise fsync instead.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] When provided with a corrupt database, such as one produced by fuzzing, LMDB may crash.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB's author considers the case unlikely to be concerning but has produced a partial fix in a separate branch.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] In June 2013, Oracle changed the license of Berkeley DB (a related project) from the Sleepycat license to the Affero General Public License, thus restricting its use in a wide variety of applications.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] This caused the Debian project to exclude the library from 6.0 onwards.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] It was also criticized that this license is not friendly to commercial redistributors.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The discussion was sparked over whether the same licensing change could happen to LMDB.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Author Howard Chu clarified that LMDB is part of the OpenLDAP project, which had its BSD-style license before he joined, and it will stay like it.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] No copyright is transferred to anybody by checking in, which would make a similar move like Oracle's impossible.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The Berkeley DB license issue has caused major Linux distributions such as Debian to completely phase out their use of Berkeley DB, with a preference for LMDB.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] There are wrappers for several programming languages, such as C++, Java, Python, Lua, Rust, Go, Ruby, Objective C, Objective CAML, JavaScript, C#, Perl, PHP, Tcl and Common Lisp.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] A complete list of wrappers may be found on the main web site.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Howard Chu ported SQLite 3.7.7.1 to use LMDB instead of its original B-tree code, calling the result SQLightning.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] One cited insert test of 1000 records was 20 times faster (than the original SQLite with its B-Tree implementation).
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB is available as a backing store for other open source projects including Cyrus SASL, Heimdal Kerberos, and OpenDKIM.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] It is also available in some other NoSQL projects like MemcacheDB and Mapkeeper.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] LMDB was used to make the in-memory store Redis persist data on disk.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The existing back-end in Redis showed pathological behaviour in rare cases, and a replacement was sought.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The baroque API of LMDB was criticized though, forcing a lot of coding to get simple things done.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] However, its performance and reliability during testing was considerably better than the alternative back-end stores that were tried.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] An up-to-date list of applications using LMDB is maintained on the main web site.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Many popular free software projects distribute or include support for LMDB, often as the primary or sole storage mechanism.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Additionally, as LMDB was primarily developed for use in OpenLDAP, its developers are focused mainly on the development and maintenance of OpenLDAP, not on LMDB per se.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The presentation did spark other database developers to dissect the code in-depth to understand how and why it works.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Database developer Oren Eini wrote a 12-part series of articles on his analysis of LMDB, beginning July 9, 2013.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The conclusion was in the lines of "impressive codebase ... dearly needs some love", mainly because of too long methods and code duplication.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] This review, conducted by a .NET developer with no former experience of C, concluded on August 22, 2013, with "beyond my issues with the code, the implementation is really quite brilliant.
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] The way LMDB manages to pack so much functionality by not doing things is quite impressive...
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] I learned quite a lot from the project, and it has been frustrating, annoying and fascinating experience".
[src:lmdb/lightning-memory-mapped-database] Multiple other reviews cover LMDB in various languages including Chinese.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Symas LMDB is an extraordinarily fast, memory-efficient database we developed for the OpenLDAP Project.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] With memory-mapped files, LMDB has the read performance of a pure in-memory database while retaining the persistence of standard disk-based databases.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Bottom line, with only 32KB of object code, LMDB may seem tiny.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Compact and efficient are two sides of a coin; that’s part of what makes LMDB so powerful.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Symas offers fixed-price, Gold support or Enterprise source level support to those using LMDB in their applications.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Please contact Sales by phone or email for additional information.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Search the discussions on the OpenLDAP mailing lists.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Development occurs in the OpenLDAP Project‘s git repo in the mdb.master branch.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] A clone of just the LMDB code is also available on Github.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Symas LMDB has been written about, talked about, and utilized in a variety of impressive products and publications.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] We invite you to learn more on this specific “Technical Information” page.
[src:lmdb/lmdb] Thinking about switching your application to LMDB?
[src:lmdb/lmdb] We will be happy to provide developer support or porting services to help you transition your application to LMDB.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] A **memory-mapped file** is a segment of virtual memory that has been assigned a direct byte-for-byte correlation with some portion of a file or file-like resource.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] This resource is typically a file that is physically present on disk, but can also be a device, shared memory object, or other resource that an operating system can reference through a file descriptor.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Once present, this correlation between the file and the memory space permits applications to treat the mapped portion as if it were primary memory.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] 1969) implementation of this was the **PMAP** system call on the DEC-20's TOPS-20 operating system, a feature used by Software House's System-1022 database system.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Two decades after the release of TOPS-20's PMAP, Windows NT was given Growable Memory-Mapped Files (GMMF).
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Since "`CreateFileMapping` function requires a size to be passed to it" and altering a file's size is not readily accommodated, a GMMF API was developed.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Use of GMMF requires declaring the maximum to which the file size can grow, but no unused space is wasted.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The benefit of memory mapping a file is increasing I/O performance, especially when used on large files.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For small files, memory-mapped files can result in a waste of slack space as memory maps are always aligned to the page size, which is mostly 4 KiB.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Therefore, a 5 KiB file will allocate 8 KiB and thus 3 KiB are wasted.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Accessing memory mapped files is faster than using direct read and write operations for two reasons.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Firstly, a system call is orders of magnitude slower than a simple change to a program's local memory.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Secondly, in most operating systems the memory region mapped actually *is* the kernel's page cache (file cache), meaning that no copies need to be created in user space.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Certain application-level memory-mapped file operations also perform better than their physical file counterparts.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Applications can access and update data in the file directly and in-place, as opposed to seeking from the start of the file or rewriting the entire edited contents to a temporary location.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Since the memory-mapped file is handled internally in pages, linear file access (as seen, for example, in flat file data storage or configuration files) requires disk access only when a new page boundary is crossed, and can write larger sections of the file to disk in a single operation.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] A possible benefit of memory-mapped files is a "lazy loading", thus using small amounts of RAM even for a very large file.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Trying to load the entire contents of a file that is significantly larger than the amount of memory available can cause severe thrashing as the operating system reads from disk into memory and simultaneously writes pages from memory back to disk.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Memory-mapping may not only bypass the page file completely, but also allow smaller page-sized sections to be loaded as data is being edited, similarly to demand paging used for programs.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The memory mapping process is handled by the virtual memory manager, which is the same subsystem responsible for dealing with the page file.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Memory mapped files are loaded into memory one entire page at a time.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The page size is selected by the operating system for maximum performance.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Since page file management is one of the most critical elements of a virtual memory system, loading page sized sections of a file into physical memory is typically a very highly optimized system function.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Persisted files are associated with a source file on a disk.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The data is saved to the source file on the disk once the last process is finished.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] These memory-mapped files are suitable for working with extremely large source files.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Non-persisted files are not associated with a file on a disk.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] When the last process has finished working with the file, the data is lost.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] These files are suitable for creating shared memory for inter-process communications (IPC).
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The major reason to choose memory mapped file I/O is performance.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The standard I/O approach is costly due to system call overhead and memory copying.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The memory-mapped approach has its cost in minor page faults—when a block of data is loaded in page cache, but is not yet mapped into the process's virtual memory space.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] In some circumstances, memory mapped file I/O can be substantially slower than standard file I/O.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Another drawback of memory-mapped files relates to a given architecture's address space: a file larger than the addressable space can have only portions mapped at a time, complicating reading it.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For example, a 32-bit architecture such as Intel's IA-32 can only directly address 4 GiB or smaller portions of files.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] An even smaller amount of addressable space is available to individual programs—typically in the range of 2 to 3 GiB, depending on the operating system kernel.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] This drawback however is virtually eliminated on modern 64-bit architecture.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] mmap also tends to be less scalable than standard means of file I/O, since many operating systems, including Linux, have a cap on the number of cores handling page faults.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Extremely fast devices, such as modern NVM Express SSDs, are capable of making the overhead a real concern.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] I/O errors on the underlying file (e.g. its removable drive is unplugged or optical media is ejected, disk full when writing, etc.) while accessing its mapped memory are reported to the application as the SIGSEGV/SIGBUS signals on POSIX, and the EXECUTE_IN_PAGE_ERROR structured exception on Windows.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] All code accessing mapped memory must be prepared to handle these errors, which don't normally occur when accessing memory.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Only hardware architectures with an MMU can support memory-mapped files.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] On architectures without an MMU, the operating system can copy the entire file into memory when the request to map it is made, but this is extremely wasteful and slow if only a little bit of the file will be accessed, and can only work for files that will fit in available memory.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Most memory-mapping systems use a technique called demand paging, where the file is loaded into physical memory in subsets (one page each), and only when that page is actually referenced.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] In the specific case of executable files, this permits the OS to selectively load only those portions of a process image that actually need to execute.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Another common use for memory-mapped files is to share memory between multiple processes.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] In modern protected mode operating systems, processes are generally not permitted to access memory space that is allocated for use by another process.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] (A program's attempt to do so causes invalid page faults or segmentation violations.) There are a number of techniques available to safely share memory, and memory-mapped file I/O is one of the most popular.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Two or more applications can simultaneously map a single physical file into memory and access this memory.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For example, the Microsoft Windows operating system provides a mechanism for applications to memory-map a shared segment of the system's page file itself and share data via this section.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Most modern operating systems or runtime environments support some form of memory-mapped file access.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The Microsoft Windows operating systems also support a group of API functions for this purpose, such as CreateFileMapping().
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The Java programming language provides classes and methods to access memory mapped files, such as `FileChannel`.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Furthermore, Java uses memory-mapped approach to load specific classes to decrease the class loading time in JVM - Java Class Data Sharing.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The D programming language supports memory mapped files in its standard library (std.mmfile module)..
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Ruby has a gem (library) called Mmap, which implements memory-mapped file objects.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Rust does not provide any mmap functionality in the standard library but there exists a third-party crate (library) called memmap2.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Since version 1.6, Python has included a mmap module in its Standard Library.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Details of the module vary according to whether the host platform is Windows or Unix-like.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For Perl there are several modules available for memory mapping files on the CPAN, such as Sys::Mmap and File::Map.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] In the Microsoft .NET runtime, P/Invoke can be used to use memory mapped files directly through the Windows API.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Managed access (P/Invoke not necessary) to memory mapped files was introduced in version 4 of the runtime (see Memory-Mapped Files).
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For previous versions, there are third-party libraries which provide managed API's. .NET have the `MemoryMappedFile` class.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] PHP supported memory-mapping techniques in a number of native file access functions such as `file_get_contents()` but has removed this in 5.3 (see revision log).
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] For the R programming language there exists a library on CRAN called bigmemory which uses the Boost library and provides memory-mapped backed arrays directly in R.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The package ff offers memory-mapped vectors, matrices, arrays and data frames.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The J programming language has supported memory-mapped files since at least 2005.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] It includes support for boxed array data, and single datatype files.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] Support can be loaded from 'data/jmf' J's Jdb and JD database engines use memory-mapped files for column stores.
[src:lmdb/memory-mapped-file] The Julia programming language has support for I/O of memory-mapped binary files through the `Mmap` module within the Standard Library.
